{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487078"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:56:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:56:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"247"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/247"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.01,0.44,0.01,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"247"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101298"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/247"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"247"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83728"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"3051"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31633"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42987"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101298"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of severe pain in the first metatarsophalangeal joint of his right foot. He has a medical history of alcohol dependence (drinks one cask of wine per day), hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus (diet-controlled), myelodysplasia, and gout. His regular medications include allopurinol and perindopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The first metatarsophalangeal joint of his right foot is red, swollen, warm and exquisitely tender to touch with restricted range of movement. Blood tests show creatinine 122 \u00b5mol/L (45-90), urea 10.0 mmol/L (2.7-8.0) and urate 0.60 mmol/L (0.15-0.45).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral ibuprofen","Subcutaneous fentanyl","Intra-articular methylprednisolone","Oral morphine","Oral colchicine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an acute flare of gout affecting a single joint. The management options for acute gout include NSAIDs, colchicine, and glucocorticoids, with the choice guided by individual patient factors and pattern of involvement. The classic presentation in the first metatarsophalangeal joint (podagra) along with hyperuricaemia confirms the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntra-articular methylprednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice in this case. With monoarticular involvement, local glucocorticoid injection provides rapid relief while avoiding systemic effects. This is particularly advantageous given this patient\u0027s multiple comorbidities including renal impairment, diabetes, and myelodysplasia. The local administration means minimal systemic absorption and therefore minimal impact on blood glucose control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral ibuprofen\u003C/strong\u003E would typically be an effective first-line treatment for acute gout, but is contraindicated in this patient due to his renal impairment (elevated creatinine and urea). NSAIDs can worsen kidney function and increase the risk of gastrointestinal bleeding, particularly concerning given his alcohol use. They can also worsen hypertension and increase cardiovascular risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral colchicine\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in this patient due to his myelodysplasia. Colchicine can cause bone marrow suppression and should be avoided in patients with pre-existing blood dyscrasias. Additionally, colchicine requires dose adjustment in renal impairment and can have significant gastrointestinal side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous fentanyl\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral morphine\u003C/strong\u003E are not appropriate treatments for acute gout. While opioids may provide pain relief, they do not address the underlying inflammatory process and are not recommended as first-line therapy. Furthermore, prescribing opioids to a patient with alcohol dependence carries additional risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe elevated urate level (0.60 mmol/L) indicates poor control of chronic gout. The patient should be counselled about medication compliance with allopurinol (which should be continued throughout an acute flare, as stopping means loss of its therapeutic effect and a rise in urate level) and lifestyle modifications, particularly alcohol reduction, as alcohol interferes with uric acid excretion and can trigger acute attacks. Dietary advice regarding purine-rich foods should also be provided.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Choice of initial treatment in acute gout is guided by renal function, comorbidities, and pattern of involvement.","Intra-articular glucocorticoids are preferred for monoarticular gout when systemic treatments are contraindicated.","NSAIDs should be avoided in renal impairment and colchicine is contraindicated in blood dyscrasias.","Alcohol reduction and medication compliance are crucial for long-term gout management."],"references":["Graf SW, Whittle SL, Wechalekar MD, Moi JH, Barrett C, Hill CL, et al. Australian and New Zealand recommendations for the diagnosis and management of gout: integrating systematic literature review and expert opinion in the 3e Initiative. Int J Rheum Dis 2015;18(3):341\u201351.","Robinson PC, Stamp LK. The management of gout: Much has changed. Aust Fam Physician. 2016 May;45(5):299-302. PMID: 27166465. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2016/may/the-management-of-gout-much-has-changed"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83728"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"247"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83728"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-01T10:14:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-01T10:14:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"247"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101298"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"